The study species is 
\f7\i \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Prunus mahaleb
\f4\i0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
 (L.), a rosaceous tree that in SE Spanish populations is gynodioecious, with individuals producing hermaphrodite flowers and others with androsterile flowers, which behave as functional females. In the southern Iberian Peninsula this species flowers between mid-May and mid-June at high elevations (over 1300 m) and insects, mainly bees (Hymenoptera: Andrenidae, Apidae) and flies (Diptera: Calliphoridae, Syrphidae) act as pollen vectors. 
\f7\i \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
P. mahaleb
\f4\i0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
 produces fleshy fruits (drupaceous) (Fig. 1) with 1 seed per fruit. In late July fleshy fruits are produced and consumed by frugivorous animals that disperse the seeds until late August or early September.\
